<body>
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Car Catalytic Converter Guide</h1>

    <!-- Purpose Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Purpose</h2>
      <p>The catalytic converter is a key component of the car's exhaust system, designed to reduce harmful emissions by converting toxic gases into less harmful substances. It plays a critical role in reducing air pollution and ensuring compliance with environmental regulations.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- How It Works Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>How It Works</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>The catalytic converter uses a catalyst (usually platinum, palladium, or rhodium) to trigger chemical reactions.</li>
        <li>It converts carbon monoxide (CO) into carbon dioxide (CO₂), hydrocarbons (HC) into water (H₂O), and nitrogen oxides (NOₓ) into nitrogen (N₂) and oxygen (O₂).</li>
        <li>It operates at high temperatures, making it most effective when the engine is warm.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Components Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Components</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Catalyst:</strong> A honeycomb-like structure coated with precious metals that facilitate chemical reactions.</li>
        <li><strong>Heat Shield:</strong> Protects the converter and surrounding components from excessive heat.</li>
        <li><strong>Oxygen Sensors:</strong> Monitor the oxygen levels in the exhaust to optimize the converter's efficiency.</li>
        <li><strong>Inlet and Outlet Pipes:</strong> Allow exhaust gases to enter and exit the converter.</li>
        <li><strong>Substrate:</strong> A ceramic or metallic structure that supports the catalyst and maximizes surface area for reactions.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Maintenance Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Maintenance</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Regularly inspect the catalytic converter for physical damage, such as dents or cracks.</li>
        <li>Ensure the engine is running efficiently, as poor combustion can damage the converter.</li>
        <li>Check for signs of clogging, such as reduced engine performance or increased exhaust backpressure.</li>
        <li>Replace the catalytic converter if it fails or becomes clogged beyond repair.</li>
        <li>Use the correct fuel and avoid leaded gasoline, as it can damage the catalyst.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Signs of Catalytic Converter Issues Section -->
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Signs of Catalytic Converter Issues</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Check Engine Light:</strong> A malfunctioning catalytic converter can trigger the check engine light.</li>
        <li><strong>Reduced Performance:</strong> Poor acceleration or reduced engine power may indicate a clogged converter.</li>
        <li><strong>Unusual Smells:</strong> A rotten egg smell from the exhaust may indicate a failing converter.</li>
        <li><strong>Increased Emissions:</strong> Failed emissions tests or visible smoke from the exhaust.</li>
        <li><strong>Rattling Noises:</strong> A damaged or broken internal substrate can cause rattling sounds.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Images Section -->
    <div class="images">
      <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/1d/DodgeCatCon.jpg" alt="Catalytic Converter Image 1">
